00:17:08.660 --> 00:17:12.050 align:middle line:84%
So I think it's easy to show
that modern versions of wheat

00:17:12.050 --> 00:17:15.260 align:middle line:84%
and grains have been
dramatically changed

00:17:15.260 --> 00:17:18.220 align:middle line:84%
at the hands of geneticists
and agribusiness.

00:17:18.220 --> 00:17:20.270 align:middle line:84%
But I'd push that
argument even farther,

00:17:20.270 --> 00:17:23.609 align:middle line:84%
that grains were always
a problem for humans.

00:17:23.609 --> 00:17:25.670 align:middle line:90%
So you know who does know this?

00:17:25.670 --> 00:17:27.020 align:middle line:90%
The anthropologists.

00:17:27.020 --> 00:17:28.940 align:middle line:84%
They've known this
for several decades,

00:17:28.940 --> 00:17:34.520 align:middle line:84%
that when humans were largely
hunter gatherers or conducted

00:17:34.520 --> 00:17:37.220 align:middle line:84%
limited farming, like
growing fruit and those kinds

00:17:37.220 --> 00:17:41.060 align:middle line:84%
of plants, there was
almost no tooth decay.

00:17:41.060 --> 00:17:43.850 align:middle line:84%
There was very
little bone disease.

00:17:43.850 --> 00:17:46.850 align:middle line:84%
And men were taller,
and likewise women.

00:17:46.850 --> 00:17:49.970 align:middle line:84%
When humans turned to the
seeds of grasses, grains,

00:17:49.970 --> 00:17:52.390 align:middle line:84%
which they did so in desperation
at first, around 10,000,

00:17:52.390 --> 00:17:55.890 align:middle line:84%
12,000 years ago-- that is
on a large systematic scale--

00:17:55.890 --> 00:17:58.340 align:middle line:84%
there was an explosion
in tooth decay.

00:17:58.340 --> 00:18:01.160 align:middle line:84%
Prior to the consumption
of grains, 1% to 3%

00:18:01.160 --> 00:18:05.330 align:middle line:84%
of all teeth recovered showed
decay or tooth loss or abscess.

00:18:05.330 --> 00:18:09.260 align:middle line:84%
After the incorporation of
grains, 16 to 49% of teeth

00:18:09.260 --> 00:18:11.510 align:middle line:84%
showed decay,
abscess formation, or

00:18:11.510 --> 00:18:13.460 align:middle line:90%
some other destructive effect.

00:18:13.460 --> 00:18:15.650 align:middle line:90%
Men lost five inches in height.

00:18:15.650 --> 00:18:17.300 align:middle line:84%
Women lost three
inches in height.

00:18:17.300 --> 00:18:19.550 align:middle line:84%
That was an effect that only
lasted several centuries.

00:18:19.550 --> 00:18:20.925 align:middle line:84%
There was a partial
accommodation

00:18:20.925 --> 00:18:23.630 align:middle line:84%
to the deleterious effects
of grains, but nonetheless,

00:18:23.630 --> 00:18:26.330 align:middle line:84%
evidence of some
very peculiar effect.

00:18:26.330 --> 00:18:28.460 align:middle line:90%
There was more bone disease.

00:18:28.460 --> 00:18:31.420 align:middle line:84%
There was evidence for iron
deficiency anemia showing up.

00:18:31.420 --> 00:18:33.470 align:middle line:90%
It shows up in the bones.

00:18:33.470 --> 00:18:36.440 align:middle line:84%
The anthropologists call
it porotic hyperostosis.

00:18:36.440 --> 00:18:38.420 align:middle line:84%
In other words,
when humans turned

00:18:38.420 --> 00:18:43.430 align:middle line:84%
the seeds of grasses for
substance to survive,

00:18:43.430 --> 00:18:45.890 align:middle line:84%
an explosion of health
problems appeared.

00:18:45.890 --> 00:18:49.520 align:middle line:84%
This is well-established in
the anthropological record.

00:18:49.520 --> 00:18:54.140 align:middle line:84%
We also see this very same
phenomenon, not so much today,

00:18:54.140 --> 00:18:55.700 align:middle line:84%
but in the last
two centuries, when

00:18:55.700 --> 00:18:58.640 align:middle line:84%
primitive cultures, who
were hunters and gatherers,

00:18:58.640 --> 00:19:02.750 align:middle line:84%
whether it was in New
Zealand or Northwest Pacific

